{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2016}} '''William Meacham''' is an American archaeologist living and working in Hong Kong since 1970. Meacham has written several books on archaeology in southern China.<ref>[http://www.chm.hku.hk/meacham.html from a presentation of Meacham when presenting an article at the Centre for the Humanities and Medicine at The University of Hong Kong]</ref>
In 1977 he published an article on South China archaeology in the journal ''Current Anthropology'',<ref>Continuity and local evolution in the Neolithic of South China: a non-nuclear approach. ''Current Anthropology''. by William Meacham. 1977 18(3): 419-440</ref> opposing the then general consensus that innovations spread south from the Central Plains of North China. This "nuclear area hypothesis" was promoted by [[Kwang-chih Chang]], the prominent doyen of ancient China archaeology. In 2000, in a preface to his own Festschrift, Chang acknowledged: "On the concept of 'Regional Cultures,' I was very much a late-comer. Judith Treistman (1972) and William Meacham (1977) were both pioneers on this question."<ref>Reflections on Chinese Archaeology in the Second Half of the Twentieth Century. ''Journal of East Asian Archaeology''. by Kwang-Chih Chang. 2001 3(1):5-19</ref>
Meacham has written several papers<ref name= "Article">William Meacham, [http://www.shroud.com/meacham2.htm "The Authentication of the Turin Shroud, An Issue in Archeological Epistemology"], ''Current Anthropology'', 1983 24(3): 283-311</ref> and a book<ref>William Meacham, "The Rape of the Turin Shroud", 2005, {{ISBN|1-4116-5769-1}}</ref> on the restoration of the [[Shroud of Turin]] in 2002, where Meacham is questioning the restoration methods used by the [[Catholic Church]].
He recently conducted a successful search to locate a Confederate burial ground of 227 soldiers in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.<ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/nov/1/diggers-search-for-soldiers-final-resting-place/ initial report in the ''Washington Times'']</ref> .<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UXbSq14_BLQ latest report by Nashville TV station]</ref> In researching the epidemic that killed these soldiers encamped at Hopkinsville in 1861, Meacham developed a hypothesis that the disease, at the time called "Black Measles", was influenza. He published a lengthy article on the subject.<ref>William Meacham, [http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/191159/2/Content.pdf Was measles a powerful killer, as widely believed, during the Civil War?] ''Journal of Civil War Medicine '' 17, 4, 2013</ref>
